                        <div class="visually-hidden">
                <span itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Morning Agenda: Uber and Didi Chuxing Team Up in China</span>
                <span class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
                    By Amie Tsang                </span>
                <!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2016-08-01T09:49:20+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">August 1, 2016 5:49 am</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">August 1, 2016 5:49 am</span>            </div>
			<div class="entry-content">
			<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//news.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/morning-agenda-uber-and-didi-chuxing-team-up-in-china/" data-title="Morning Agenda: Uber and Didi Chuxing Team Up in China" data-description="Oracle Has a Cloud Problem | Yahoo Sale Leaves Little Choice for Shareholders">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>UBER AND DIDI CHUXING TEAM UP IN CHINA</strong> The battle for ride-sharing in China is over. Didi Chuxing plans to buy Uber China, according to people with knowledge of the deal. After spending tens of millions of dollars every month fighting for market share, the two companies will combine into a new one worth about <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/08/02/business/dealbook/china-uber-didi-chuxing.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">$35 billion</a>.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;I&#8217;ve learned that being successful is about listening to your head as well as following your heart,&#8221; Travis Kalanick, Uber&#8217;s chief executive, wrote in a blog post intended to announce the deal. &#8220;Uber and Didi Chuxing are investing billions of dollars in China and both have yet to turn a profit there.&#8221; <a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-08-01/uber-said-to-merge-china-business-with-didi-in-35-billion-deal?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">Bloomberg</a>, which earlier reported the deal, said that Uber had lost more than $2 billion in China.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors in Uber China will receive a 20 percent stake in the new company and Didi will make a $1 billion investment in Uber Global.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>ORACLE HAS A CLOUD PROBLEM</strong> Oracle has never really had a problem spending money, having shelled out for dozens of companies over the last 11 years. But as the new owner of NetSuite, it faces the challenge of integrating its new acquisition into its global network of data centers. And it will have to show that it can rein in competitors that have been stealing customers with fresher technology and cloud computing, as Oracle has taken its time shifting from its older and more expensive technology.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Oracle figured it could distribute NetSuite&#8217;s e-commerce and manufacturing software via its cloud, while using it to reach smaller companies that have so far been unable to afford Oracle&#8217;s high-cost product. And that task falls to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/technology/oracle-thomas-kurian-software-netsuite.html?ref=dealbook&amp;_r=&amp;nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">Thomas Kurian</a>, the president of product development, who has been overseeing Oracle&#8217;s reinvention.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> The latest I.S.M. manufacturing report will be published at 10 a.m. Elizabeth Holmes, the founder and chief executive of Theranos, will speak at the annual meeting of the American Association for Clinical Chemistry in Philadelphia at 4:30 p.m.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>YAHOO SALE LEAVES LITTLE CHOICE FOR SHAREHOLDERS</strong> The Yahoo sale is not the sale of a publicly traded company &#8211; it&#8217;s the sale of the Yahoo subsidiary. The $4.8 billion will be paid to Yahoo, and its shareholders will not receive any money unless Yahoo pays it out in a dividend. They will be left holding shares in the remaining company. Although they have a vote on the sale, there will be no appraisal rights. So anyone who thinks the price is inadequate is out of luck, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/07/30/business/dealbook/yahoos-sale-to-verizon-leaves-shareholders-with-little-say.html?ref=dealbook&amp;nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">Steven Davidoff Solomon explains.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Verizon, for its part, will be agitating to make the most of its role in this deal. It has been trying to reinvent itself since before it bought AOL and Yahoo, seeking to shake its reputation as a big, boring telephone company to be considered a digital player. &#8220;People act like Google and Facebook have already won. But nobody owns the future,&#8221; said Tim Armstrong, AOL&#8217;s chief executive, who will oversee the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/07/31/business/media/yahoo-and-the-online-universe-according-to-verizon.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">integration with Yahoo.</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Contact <a href="mailto:amie.tsang@nytimes.com">amie.tsang@nytimes.com</a></em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//dealbook.blogs.nytimes.com/category/mergers-acquisitions/?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">MERGERS &amp; ACQUISITIONS Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Chinese Group to Pay $4.4 Billion for Caesars&#8217; Mobile Games</strong> The deal with Caesars Interactive Entertainment is a sign that investors are willing to pay increasingly large sums for smartphone games.<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/business/dealbook/china-caesars-mobile-games-playtika.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">NYT Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Sotheby&#8217;s New Major Shareholder Is Already a Power in Chinese Art</strong> Taikang Life Insurance, run by Chen Dongsheng, now holds 13.5 percent of Sotheby&#8217;s stock, evidence of how far China has risen in the art business.<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/arts/design/sothebys-chen-dongsheng-china-art.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">NYT Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Acquisitive Chinese Conglomerate Planning Asset Sales</strong> Liang Xinjun, chief executive of Fosun International, said the group was preparing to sell as much as $6 billion in assets in an effort to repay debt and improve its credit rating.<br />
<a href="//www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-07-31/fosun-plans-sale-of-assets-in-reversal-of-15-billion-m-a-spree?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">BLOOMBERG</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>GlaxoSmithKline and Alphabet Create $715 Million Bioelectronics Company</strong> GlaxoSmithKline and Verily Life Sciences, Alphabet&#8217;s life science unit, will contribute $715.12 million to a new company that will focus on fighting diseases by targeting electrical signals in the body.<br />
<a href="//www.reuters.com/article/us-gsk-alphabet-idUSKCN10C1K8?feedType=RSS&amp;feedName=innovationNews&amp;nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">REUTERS</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/b/banks_and_banking/index.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">INVESTMENT BANKING Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>JPMorgan Chase Retreats From Settlement Role in Treasury Market</strong> The decision leaves Bank of New York Mellon as the lone company handling the settlement of government debt for big bond brokers and poses a new challenge for regulators seeking to bolster the market&#8217;s capacity to withstand shocks.<br />
<a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/this-boring-service-is-suddenly-a-big-concern-for-treasurys-1469995801?mod=asia_home&amp;nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">THE WALL STREET JOURNAL</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Goldman Sachs Faces More Questions from British Officials</strong> British members of Parliament have asked Goldman to give details of paid work it has done for Tina Green, who is married to the retailer Sir Philip Green, after a parliamentary investigation accused the bank of lending credibility to the &#8220;otherwise questionable&#8221; sale of the department store chain BHS.<br />
<a href="//www.ft.com/cms/s/0/6c6242d2-54e4-11e6-9664-e0bdc13c3bef.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">THE FINANCIAL TIMES</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">For the latest updates, go to <a href="//www.nytimes.com/pages/business/dealbook/index.html">NYTimes.com/DealBook</a><br />
<a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/h/hedge_funds/index.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">HEDGE FUNDS Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Hedge Funds Sue Standard Chartered</strong> A group of hedge funds that includes Arrowgrass, Highbridge and Pine River is suing Standard Chartered over who should hold the losses on derivatives contracts tied to the bonds of an Indian car-parts company.<br />
<a href="//www.ft.com/cms/s/0/573fda26-5715-11e6-9f70-badea1b336d4.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">THE FINANCIAL TIMES</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/i/initial_public_offerings/index.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">I.P.O./OFFERINGS Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Companies Choose Sales Over I.P.O.s</strong> Mergers and acquisitions have not slumped as sharply in the United States as initial public offerings, and many private equity firms are looking for a quick exit from older investments.<br />
<a href="//www.wsj.com/articles/more-companies-are-choosing-a-sale-over-an-ipo-1470007753?mod=asia_home&amp;nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">THE WALL STREET JOURNAL</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/subjects/c/credit_crisis/financial_regulatory_reform/index.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">LEGAL/REGULATORY Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Why Is the Stock Market So High?</strong> Ask the Bond Market Bonds have risen sharply in value, and their yields have plummeted. That has made stock prices look cheap and dividends seem generous, driving up the market.<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/07/31/your-money/why-is-the-stock-market-so-high-ask-the-bond-market.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">NYT Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Back-Stabbing and Threats of a &#8216;Suicide Parachute&#8217; at Hershey</strong> A leaked memo reveals strife in the trust that controls the Hershey Company and the school for at-risk children started by its founder, Milton Hershey.<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/07/31/business/dealbook/back-stabbing-and-threats-of-a-suicide-parachute-at-hershey.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">NYT Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Publicis Ad Executive Sidelined by Gender Diversity Comments</strong> The executive, Kevin Roberts, chairman of Saatchi &amp; Saatchi and head coach at Publicis Groupe, said the issue of gender diversity was &#8220;way worse&#8221; in other industries.<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/business/publicis-ad-executive-sidelined-by-gender-diversity-comments.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">NYT Â»</a></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Clinton? Trump? Either Way, Count on Deficit Spending to Rise</strong> Both candidates have some expensive proposals, and economists are coming around to the view that an increase in borrowing might be a good thing.<br />
<a href="//www.nytimes.com/2016/08/01/business/economy/clinton-trump-either-way-count-on-deficit-spending-to-rise.html?nl=dealbook&amp;emc=edit_dlbkam_20160801">NYT Â»</a></p>
